Here's a tip on how to react to negative thoughts: consider saying to yourself "I can't help my thoughts to come, but I need to stop reacting to them as if they insist on being true." or  etwas like "Think emergency, act routine" so you ensure that you don't act on impulse based on a false sense of an emergency.&#x20;

Remind yourself that your name is not paranoid schizophrenic <your name here>. You are not one with your thoughts. There is a distance between your thoughts and your identity, your sense of self. And try to create a distance by reminding yourself who you are separate from those thoughts that flail about in a wild fashion.&#x20;

So take a little walk to the surface here. Breathe in for a count of four, like when you're literally feeling overheated and out of breath -- that one, two, three, four -- and then breathe out for a count of four, while focusing on the sounds around you outside, inside and outside the air on your face. Store this little walk anytime you want to do this.&#x20;

It might be helpful to set boundaries with your mom around your personal space and time. Let her know that you need some alone time to recharge and that it's not because you don't care about her.

Trusting your gut is the primary way your Self lets you know things to consider about thinking sadness. Think of things you know how to accomplish. It doesn't have to be a big thing that you like. It can be something as simple as drinking a cold drink. A small pleasure helps you feel like you do control parts of your life.&#x20;

Here is something as simple as being able to feel neutral in one part of your life. Another way to will something that's adverse is to think, "Let me follow my fear, maybe I can find what triggers the sadness in the first place."&#x20;

Let's find some articles or other content that might be soothing and read them in some calming voice. I can do that for you. Would you like some calming music or nature sounds in the background as I read?&#x20;

Also, maybe try putting on some comfortable clothes and finding a cozy spot to settle in to make the experience even more soothing for you. At the same time, you can try some more grounding strategies.&#x20;

Consider the five-four-three-two-one grounding exercise as you try to become more immersed in your present surroundings. Focus on the cushion under you, the floor beneath your feet, and try to almost imagine roots connecting you to the earth. It might make you feel safer. Think about how the air feels on your skin. Can you smell any food nearby?&#x20;

Your thoughts can be yucky but you can distract yourself with water during these moments when sadness makes you feel like you can barely move. The little things can save you from feeling overwhelmed. Take a swig of water, tell yourself you can do it.&#x20;

Breathe, do a funny voice, literally drink water, or say, in yet another funny voice, "I feel overemotional." This dissociation sounds nuts but literally the voice-acting breaks the overwhelm pattern. Other people know they can emotionally separate thoughts from themselves by literally "voicing" them with almost any characatured voice.&#x20;

Now imagine yourself in a safe space performing anything that keeps you from overthinking for you. A ton of people always uplift others by telling them to "go live their best lives." Sounds doable. Sometimes it sounds fun – but so difficult. But once you realize it is doable, and that you have the immediate power to think a happy thought, it starts sounding exciting. It starts sounding viable. You have the option right now. Say it out loud. But which voices now come to mind? If only you can choose to turn on your TV and change to something that brings you actual germane beauty instead of harm. If you can turn on up or down moments inside from focusing on 8 plus 5, 6 plus 2, or, literally for a moment even, 10 minus 1 you can pull your mind away to things that give you life, etc.
